I really love cumin.

00:40:34.620 --> 00:40:35.870
I just love cumin.

00:40:35.870 --> 00:40:39.380
I love fresh fennel.

00:40:39.380 --> 00:40:42.260
But I also like
growing things at home.

00:40:42.260 --> 00:40:45.067
So we have a curry tree at home.

00:40:45.067 --> 00:40:47.150
It's like four years old,
but it's only this tall.

00:40:47.150 --> 00:40:50.270
It's unbelievably slow grower.

00:40:50.270 --> 00:40:56.310
But with those three things,
you can just make so much food.

00:40:56.310 --> 00:40:59.240
But black pepper is one of those
things that I have to have.

00:40:59.240 --> 00:41:01.220
And we bang through--
our black pepper grinder

00:41:01.220 --> 00:41:05.230
is about this big, and we rip
through this olive oil, and one

00:41:05.230 --> 00:41:06.640
this big, every month.

00:41:06.640 --> 00:41:08.420
Like we just kill it.

00:41:08.420 --> 00:41:09.470
We just rip through it.

00:41:09.470 --> 00:41:12.610
If you're not just
destroying your olive oil,

00:41:12.610 --> 00:41:13.629
put it on your cereal.

00:41:13.629 --> 00:41:14.670
I don't care what you do.

00:41:14.670 --> 00:41:17.282
But it's just so good for
you, and it tastes so good.

00:41:17.282 --> 00:41:18.240
Great question, though.

00:41:18.240 --> 00:41:18.790
Thank you.

00:41:18.790 --> 00:41:19.660
Any more questions, guys?

00:41:19.660 --> 00:41:19.980
Yes, sir.

00:41:19.980 --> 00:41:22.550
AUDIENCE: Besides olive oil,
other cooking oils and choosing

00:41:22.550 --> 00:41:24.160
one versus another?

00:41:24.160 --> 00:41:26.410
NATHAN LYON: So the question
is, other than olive oil,

00:41:26.410 --> 00:41:29.810
what are other oils
that I would use?

00:41:29.810 --> 00:41:31.810
So I mainly use olive oil.

00:41:31.810 --> 00:41:34.810
And I use grape seed oil.

00:41:34.810 --> 00:41:39.590
So one is for most utilitarian
things, like the olive oil.

00:41:39.590 --> 00:41:42.420
But higher temperatures, I
would use grape seed oil,

00:41:42.420 --> 00:41:45.600
also keeping in mind that Sarah,
my girlfriend and executive

00:41:45.600 --> 00:41:48.200
sous chef, we do a lot of
drought-friendly recipes.

00:41:48.200 --> 00:41:51.350
And grapes, wine grapes don't
take a lot of water to grow,

00:41:51.350 --> 00:41:53.122
and the seeds are already there.

00:41:53.122 --> 00:41:54.080
So you just press them.

00:41:54.080 --> 00:41:56.230
So you have this double whammy.

00:41:56.230 --> 00:41:59.100
It's a neutral oil and it
has a very high smoke point,

00:41:59.100 --> 00:42:00.420
and it's heart healthy.

00:42:00.420 --> 00:42:01.000
So those two.

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:03.186
So if I'm making a
vinaigrette or a mayonnaise

00:42:03.186 --> 00:42:04.560
that I want to
flavor and I don't

00:42:04.560 --> 00:42:06.685
want it to taste like olive
oil, I would definitely

00:42:06.685 --> 00:42:07.810
use grape seed oil.

00:42:07.810 --> 00:42:10.506
And it's just a lovely
oil to work with.

00:42:10.506 --> 00:42:11.130
Great question.

00:42:11.130 --> 00:42:12.960
Thank you.

00:42:12.960 --> 00:42:14.240
Any more questions?

00:42:14.240 --> 00:42:16.540
Yes, ma'am.

00:42:16.540 --> 00:42:19.140
AUDIENCE: Do you have
any common go to recipes

00:42:19.140 --> 00:42:21.600
when you're at home and just
want to make something quick?

00:42:21.600 --> 00:42:24.190
NATHAN LYON: Because I worked
at farmers markets for 10 years,

00:42:24.190 --> 00:42:28.610
it depends what we
brought back in the truck.

00:42:28.610 --> 00:42:30.120
We always have lemons.

00:42:30.120 --> 00:42:33.050
Like right now, we have
a lot of stone fruit.

00:42:33.050 --> 00:42:37.430
The thing is, I've gotten
to the point where I just

00:42:37.430 --> 00:42:39.480
love fresh produce so much.

00:42:39.480 --> 00:42:43.550
I just love it so much that
I let it sort of guide me.

00:42:43.550 --> 00:42:45.410
So the other day we
had so many peaches,

00:42:45.410 --> 00:42:48.910
these lovely yellow
peaches, O'Henry peaches.

00:42:48.910 --> 00:42:50.080
But we had lemons, too.

00:42:50.080 --> 00:42:51.950
And I was like, oh,
well, let's just

00:42:51.950 --> 00:42:53.100
take those O'Henry peaches.

00:42:53.100 --> 00:42:54.160
We'll peel them.

00:42:54.160 --> 00:42:56.250
We'll throw in a little
bit of diced fresh mint

00:42:56.250 --> 00:42:58.600
and I'll make a simple
syrup with organic sugar.

00:42:58.600 --> 00:43:01.060
And then I'll have lemon
zest with the lemon juice.

00:43:01.060 --> 00:43:04.639
And that right there
that's peach sorbet.

00:43:04.639 --> 00:43:06.430
And all I had to do
was put it in a blender

00:43:06.430 --> 00:43:08.513
and throw it in the
processor, or in your freezer,

00:43:08.513 --> 00:43:11.520
and just put it in the processor
after it's already frozen.

00:43:11.520 --> 00:43:13.730
With the rest the peaches,
we'll make into a chutney,

00:43:13.730 --> 00:43:16.710
like a peach spicy-- fresh
ginger peach chutney.

00:43:16.710 --> 00:43:19.690
So and I learned a
lot of these things

00:43:19.690 --> 00:43:21.560
from chefs that
I've worked under.

00:43:21.560 --> 00:43:23.940
But I've also learned
a lot just from being

00:43:23.940 --> 00:43:25.700
at farmers markets,
because chances are,

00:43:25.700 --> 00:43:28.250
your local chefs are
standing right next to you

00:43:28.250 --> 00:43:31.170
getting stuff from
them, and just listening

00:43:31.170 --> 00:43:32.327
what people do with that.

00:43:32.327 --> 00:43:34.660
Because I'll do that all the
time, and I sell the stuff.

00:43:34.660 --> 00:43:37.118
But I go, oh, what would you
do-- how do you pick that out?

00:43:37.118 --> 00:43:39.700
And they go, oh, I do this and
this is what I do with that.

00:43:39.700 --> 00:43:42.366
And then I step on it and run it
over the car, whatever they do.

00:43:42.366 --> 00:43:43.650
Which is very interesting.

00:43:43.650 --> 00:43:45.774
And you learn a lot from that.

00:43:45.774 --> 00:43:47.440
But right now, because
it's summer time,

00:43:47.440 --> 00:43:50.790
and it is hot in our
house, hot, so we

00:43:50.790 --> 00:43:52.520
don't really want
to turn on the oven.

00:43:52.520 --> 00:43:57.860
So heirloom tomatoes, burrata
cheese, lots of fresh herbs.

00:43:57.860 --> 00:43:59.997
I'll turn on the grill
outside and grill up

00:43:59.997 --> 00:44:01.830
crostini with olive oil
and salt and pepper,

00:44:01.830 --> 00:44:04.891
and we'll just monch
it, just go crazy.

00:44:04.891 --> 00:44:05.390
Yeah.

00:44:05.390 --> 00:44:07.360
But whatever we do,
there's just the two of us.

00:44:07.360 --> 00:44:08.060
And we eat.

00:44:08.060 --> 00:44:09.400
We eat.

00:44:09.400 --> 00:44:10.010
Capital eat.

00:44:10.010 --> 00:44:13.020
We just Google it down.

00:44:13.020 --> 00:44:14.140
We kill it.

00:44:14.140 --> 00:44:14.980
Good question.

00:44:14.980 --> 00:44:15.919
But thank you.

00:44:15.919 --> 00:44:17.710
I mean, whatever's in
the season of summer,

00:44:17.710 --> 00:44:20.369
really, we'll just destroy it.

